<subSubSection id="C35EDEF8AC116143FF7AF7F9B233FAF9" pageId="8" pageNumber="41" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BFB8D73AC116143FF7AF7F9B233FAF9" blockId="8.[151,1437,840,1332]" pageId="8" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis id="B9305161AC116143FF7AF7F9B761FB57" bold="true" box="[197,325,1152,1178]" pageId="8" pageNumber="41">Remarks:</emphasis>
This species has previously been reported in the Southern Africa region only. It was first described on 
<taxonomicName id="4C44F6F0AC116143FE8DF7DEB7EAFB0D" box="[306,462,1191,1216]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="8" pageNumber="41" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="karoo">
<emphasis id="B9305161AC116143FE8DF7DEB7EAFB0D" box="[306,462,1191,1216]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="41">Acacia karoo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="F353CDE3AC116143FDACF7DEB48DFB0C" box="[531,681,1191,1217]" name="South Africa" pageId="8" pageNumber="41">South Africa</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFD5F082AC116143FD07F7DEB5E7FB0C" author="Ryke" box="[696,963,1191,1217]" pageId="8" pageNumber="46" refString="Ryke, P. A. J. &amp; Meyer, M. K. P. S. (1960) The parasitic and predacious mite fauna (Acarina) associated with Acacia karroo Hayne in the Western Transvaal. Libro Homenaje al Dr Eduardo Caballero y Caballero. Jubileo 1930 - 1960. Instituto Politecnico Nacional Escuela Nacional Ciencias Biologas, Mexico City, 559 - 569." type="book chapter" year="1960">
Ryke and Meyer, 
<number id="3D8C9F54AC116143FC38F7DEB5E7FB0C" box="[903,963,1191,1217]" pageId="8" pageNumber="41" value="1960.0">1960</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) and has subsequently been collected on several species of 
<emphasis id="B9305161AC116143FEC6F7B7B7F2FB2A" box="[377,470,1230,1255]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="41">
<taxonomicName id="4C44F6F0AC116143FEC6F7B7B7F6FB2A" box="[377,466,1230,1255]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="8" pageNumber="41" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Acacia</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Although it is known to occur on hosts from other plants families, it seems to exhibit preference for the family 
<taxonomicName id="4C44F6F0AC116143FD94F78DB4BBFAC3" box="[555,671,1268,1294]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="8" pageNumber="41" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
. It is however found in small numbers and thus do not seem to cause any serious threat to the thorn trees. They are reddish brown in colour.
</paragraph>
